S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Masonry
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Constructed of stones or bricks, usually quarried, shaped, and mortared.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Concreted
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Constructed of concrete, a material made of sand and gravel that is united by cement into a hardened mass used for roads, foundations, etc.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Loose Boulders
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Constructed from large stones or blocks of concrete, often placed loosely for protection against waves or water turbulence.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: hard surface
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 4:hard surface (missing definition)

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Unsurfaced
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Constructed with no extra protection, usually a term applied to roads not surfaced with a hard material.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Wooden
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Constructed from wood.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Metal
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Constructed from metal.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Glass Reinforced Plastic
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Constructed from a plastic material strengthened with fibres of glass.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Latticed
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A structure of crossed wooden or metal strips usually arranged to form a diagonal pattern of open spaces between the strips.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Glass
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: [1] Any artificial or natural substance having similar properties and composition, as fused borax, obsidian, or the like. [2] Something made of such a substance, as a windowpane.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Dolphin
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of a post or group of posts, used for mooring or warping a vessel.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Mooring Dolphin
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A post or group of posts driven into the seabed or riverbed, used as a mooring point for vessels.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Deviation Dolphin
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A post or group of posts, which a vessel may swing around for compass adjustment.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Berthing Dolphin
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A post or group of posts driven into the seabed or riverbed, used to extend the berth of a vessel by providing extra mooring points.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Fender or Breasting Dolphin
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A post or group of posts driven into the seabed or riverbed, used to assist in berthing of vessels by taking up some berthing loads; keep vessels from pressing against the pier structure; or to protect structures from possible impact by ships.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Quality of Vertical Measurement
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The reliability of the value of a sounding.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Depth Known
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The depth from the chart datum to the seabed (or to the top of a drying feature) is known.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Doubtful Sounding
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A depth that may be less than indicated.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Unreliable Sounding
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A depth that is considered to be an unreliable value.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Least Depth Known

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Maintained Depth
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The depth at which a channel is kept by human influence, usually by dredging.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Not Regularly Maintained
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Depths may be altered by human influence, but will not be routinely maintained.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: First Detection Year
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The year in which the object was originally reported.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Minimum Flight Level
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: A minimum surface of constant atmospheric pressure which is related to a specific pressure datum, (1,013.2 hectopascal (hPa) or 29.92 inches) and is separated from the consecutive flight levels by a pressure interval corresponding to 500 feet (152.4 m.)

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Shoreline Construction
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of shoreline construction based on use.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Breakwater
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A structure protecting a shore area, harbour, anchorage, or basin from waves.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Groyne
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A low artificial wall-like structure of durable material extending from the land to seaward for a particular purpose, such as to protect the coast or to force a current to scour a channel.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Mole
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A form of breakwater alongside which vessels may lie on the sheltered side only; in some cases it may lie entirely within an artificial harbour, permitting vessels to lie along both sides.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: pier (jetty)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 4:pier (jetty) (missing definition)

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Promenade Pier
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A pier built only for recreational purposes.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: wharf (quay)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 6:wharf (quay) (missing definition)

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Training Wall
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A wall or bank, often submerged, built to direct or confine the flow of a river or tidal current, or to promote a scour action.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Rip Rap
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A layer of broken rock, cobbles, boulders, or fragments of sufficient size to resist the erosive forces of flowing water and wave action.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Revetment
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Facing of stone or other material, either permanent or temporary, placed along the edge of a stream, river or canal to stabilize the bank and to protect it from the erosive action of the stream.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Sea Wall
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An embankment or wall for protection against waves or tidal action along a shore or water front.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Landing Steps
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Steps at the shoreline as the connection between land and water on different levels.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Ramp
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: (1) A sloping structure which may include rails that can either be used, as a landing place, at variable water levels, for small vessels, landing ships, or a ferry boat, or for hauling a cradle carrying a vessel. (2) An accumulation of snow that forms an inclined plane between land or land ice elements and sea ice or ice shelf. Also called drift ice foot.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Slipway
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The prepared and usually reinforced inclined surface on which keel- and bilge-blocks are laid for supporting a vessel under construction.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Fender
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A protective structure designed to cushion the impact of a vessel and prevent damage.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Solid Face Wharf
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A wharf consisting of a solid wall of concrete, masonry, wood etc., such that the water cannot circulate freely under the wharf. The type of construction affects ship-handling; for example, a solid face wharf may give shelter from tidal streams, but under certain circumstances a cushion of water may build up between such a wharf and a ship attempting to berth at it, causing difficulties in ship handling.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Open Face Wharf
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A wharf supported on piles or other structures which allow free circulation of water under the wharf.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Log Ramp
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An inclined plane used to dump logs into the water for transport, or to haul logs out of the water for processing.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Swimming Facility
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An artificial pool or swimming enclosure, especially one in the open air, which may be constructed of wire mesh or heavy netting supported by cables, buoys or piles, for swimming in.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Quay
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A wharf approximately parallel to the shoreline and accommodating ships on one side only, the other side being attached to the shore. It is usually of solid construction, as contrasted with the open pile construction usually used for piers.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: tie-up wall
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 23:tie-up wall (missing definition)

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Artificial Obstacle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Man-made structure that acts as an obstacle to landing operations.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Light Visibility
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The specific visibility of a light, with respect to the light's intensity and ease of recognition.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: High Intensity
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Non-marine lights with a higher power than marine lights and visible from well off shore (often 'Aero' lights).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Low Intensity
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Non-marine lights with lower power than marine lights.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Faint
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A decrease in the apparent intensity of a light which may occur in the case of partial obstructions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Intensified
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light in a sector is intensified (that is, has longer range than other sectors).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Unintensified
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light in a sector is unintensified (that is, has shorter range than other sectors).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Visibility Deliberately Restricted
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A light sector is deliberately reduced in intensity, for example to reduce its effect on a built-up area.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Obscured
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Said of the arc of a light sector designated by its limiting bearings in which the light is not visible from seaward.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Partially Obscured
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: This value specifies that parts of the sector are obscured.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Visible in Line of Range
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Lights that must be in line to be visible.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Sea Area
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of an area based on its physical characteristics.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Gat
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A natural or artificial passage or channel through shoals or steep banks, or across a line of banks lying between two channels.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Bank
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An elevation of the seafloor, at depths generally less than 200 m, but sufficient for safe surface navigation, commonly found on the continental shelf or near an island.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Deep
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: In oceanography, an obsolete term which was generally restricted to depths greater than 6,000 m.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Bay
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A wide indentation in the coastline generally smaller than a gulf and larger than a cove. For the purposes of the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea, a bay is a well-marked indentation whose penetration is in such proportion to the width of its mouth as to contain land locked waters and constitute more than a mere curvature of the coast.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Trench
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A long, deep, asymmetrical depression with relatively steep sides, that is associated with subduction.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Basin
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A depression of the seafloor more or less equidimensional in plan and of variable extent.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Mud Flats
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A level tract of land, as the bed of a dry lake or an area frequently uncovered at low tide. Usually in plural.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Reef
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A shallow elevation composed of consolidated material that may constitute a hazard to surface navigation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Ledge
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A rocky formation continuous with and fringing the shore.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Canyon
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An elongated, narrow, steep-sided depression that generally deepens down-slope.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Narrows
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A navigable narrow part of a bay, strait, river, etc.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Shoal
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A shallow elevation composed of unconsolidated material that may constitute a hazard to surface navigation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Knoll
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A distinct elevation with a rounded profile less than 1000m above the surrounding relief as measured from the deepest isobath that surrounds most of the feature.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Ridge
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An elongated elevation of varying complexity and size, generally having steep sides.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Seamount
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A distinct generally equidimensional elevation greater than 1000m above the surrounding relief as measured from the deepest isobath that surrounds most of the feature.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Pinnacle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Any high tower or spire-shaped pillar or rock or coral, alone or cresting a summit. It may extend above the surface of the water. It may or may not be a hazard to surface navigation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Abyssal Plain
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An extensive, flat, gently sloping or nearly level region at abyssal depths.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Plateau
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A large, relatively flat elevation that is higher than the surrounding relief with one or more relatively steep sides.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Spur
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A subordinate ridge protruding from a larger feature.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Shelf
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The flat or gently sloping region adjacent to a continent or around an island that extends from the low water line to a depth, generally about 200m, where there is a marked increase in downward slope.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Trough
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A long depression generally wide and flat bottomed with symmetrical and parallel sides.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Saddle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A broad pass or col in a ridge, rise or other elevation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Abyssal Hill
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An isolated small elevation on the deep seafloor.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Apron
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A gently dipping slope, with a smooth surface, commonly found around groups of islands and seamounts.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Archipelagic Apron
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A gentle slope with a generally smooth surface of the seafloor, characteristically found around groups of islands or seamounts.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Borderland
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A region adjacent to a continent, normally occupied by or bordering a shelf and sometimes emerging as islands, that is irregular or blocky in plan or profile, with depths well in excess of those typical of a shelf.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Continental Margin
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The zone, generally consisting of shelf, slope and continental rise, separating the continent from the deep seafloor or abyssal plain or plain. Occasionally a trench may be present in place of a continental rise.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Continental Rise
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A gentle slope rising from the oceanic depths towards the foot of a continental slope.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Escarpment
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An elongated, characteristically linear, steep slope separating horizontal or gently sloping areas of the seafloor.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Fan
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A relatively smooth, depositional feature continuously deepening away from a sediment source commonly located at the lower termination of a canyon or canyon system.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Fracture Zone
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A long narrow zone of irregular topography formed by the movement of tectonic plates associated with an offset of a spreading ridge axis, characterized by steep-sided and/or asymmetrical ridges, troughs or escarpments.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Gap
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A narrow break in a ridge, rise or other elevation.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Guyot
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A seamount having a comparatively smooth flat top.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Hill
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: [1] A small isolated elevation, smaller than a mountain. [2] A distinct elevation generally of irregular shape, less than 1000m above the surrounding relief as measured from the deepest isobath that surrounds most of the feature.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Hole
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A depression of limited extent with all sides rising steeply from a relatively flat bottom.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Levee
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A depositional embankment bordering a canyon, valley or sea channel.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Median Valley
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The axial depression of the mid-oceanic ridge system.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Moat
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An annular or partially annular depression commonly located at the base of seamounts, islands and other isolated elevations.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Mountains
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A natural elevation of the earth's surface rising more or less abruptly from the surrounding level, and attaining an altitude which, relatively to adjacent elevations, is impressive or notable.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Peak
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A conical or pointed elevation on a larger feature such as a seamount.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Province
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A geographically distinct region with a number of shared physiographic characteristics that contrast with those in the surrounding areas. This term should be modified with the generic term that best describes the majority of features in the region, for example "Seamount" in Baja California Seamount Province.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Rise
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A broad elevation that generally rises gently and smoothly from the surrounding relief.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Sea Channel
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An elongated, meandering depression, usually occurring on a gently sloping plain or fan.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Seamount Chain
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Several seamounts in linear or arcuate alignment.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: shelf-edge
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 46:shelf-edge (missing definition)

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Sill
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A relatively shallow barrier between BASINS that may inhibit water movement.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Slope
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The sloping region that deepens from a shelf to the point where there is a general decrease in gradient.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Terrace
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A flat or gently sloping region, generally long and narrow, bounded along one edge by a steeper descending slope and along the other by a steeper ascending slope.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Valley
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An elongated depression that generally widens and deepens down-slope.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Canal
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An artificial waterway with no flow, or a controlled flow, used for navigation, or for draining or irrigating land (ditch).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Lake
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A large body of water entirely surrounded by land.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: River
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A relatively large natural stream of water.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Reach
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A straight section of a river, especially a navigable river between two bends; or an arm of the sea extending into the land.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Intertidal Cay
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A low, flat island of sand, coral, etc. awash or submerged at high water.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Submarine Volcano
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A seabed volcano, submerged at the chart sounding datum, which may or may not be active.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Conveyor
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of conveyor used for moving goods from one location to another.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Aerial Cableway
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A transportation system consisting of load cables strung between pylons on which carrier units (for example: cars or buckets intended to transport people, material, and/or equipment) are suspended.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Belt Conveyor
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A conveyor along which material or people are transported by means of a moving belt.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Flume
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: An artificial channel, usually an inclined chute or trough, for carrying water to furnish power, transport logs down a mountainside, etc.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: lift/elevator
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 4:lift/elevator (missing definition)

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Road
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of a road based on size.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Motorway
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A limited access dual carriageway road specially designed for fast long-distance traffic and subject to special regulations concerning its use. It may have more than two lanes.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Major Road
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A hard surfaced (metalled) road; a main through route.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Minor Road
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A secondary road for local traffic.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Major Street
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A main road, in an urban area, for through traffic.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Minor Street
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A secondary road, in an urban area, for local traffic.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Major Light
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: A statement expressing if a light is considered to be a major light in terms of ECDIS display in a particular area.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Speed Minimum
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Rate of motion. The terms speed and velocity are often used interchangeably, but speed is a scalar, having magnitude only, while velocity is a vector quantity, having both magnitude and direction. Speed minimum is the minimum rate of travel that can occur.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Abandonment Date
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The date on which a borehole is sealed. All well-head equipment is removed and the hole plugged with cement and a steel plate cemented over the top.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Controlling Authority
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The recognised authority responsible for establishing and maintaining the administrative affairs of all matters relating to a particular field or subject.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Bottom Feature Classification
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of naturally occurring bottom features on the seabed.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Fault
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: In geology, a break of shear in the earth's crust with an observable displacement between the two sides of the break, and parallel to the plane of the break.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Sandwave
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A large mobile wave-like sediment feature in shallow water and composed of sand. The wavelength may reach 100 metres, the amplitude may be up to 20 metres.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Magnetic Intensity
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Magnetic intensity generated by the object.

S100FC:uom.S100Base:name: nanotesla

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The unit used for vessel characteristics attribute.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Metres
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The basic unit of length in the International System of Units (SI) system.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Metric Ton
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: The tonne or metric ton (U.S.), often redundantly referred to as a metric tonne, is a unit of mass equal to 1,000 kg (2,205 lb) or approximately the mass of one cubic metre of water at four degrees Celsius. It is sometimes abbreviated as mt in the United States, but this conflicts with other SI symbols. The tonne is not a unit in the International System of Units (SI), but is accepted for use with the SI. In SI units and prefixes, the tonne is a megagram (Mg). The Imperial and US customary units comparable to the tonne are both spelled ton in English, though they differ in mass. Pronunciation of tonne (the word used in the UK) and ton is usually identical, but is not too confusing unless accuracy is important as the tonne and UK long ton differ by only 1.6.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Ton
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Long ton (weight ton or imperial ton) is the name for the unit called the "ton" in the avoirdupois or Imperial system of measurements, as used in the United Kingdom and several other Commonwealth countries. It has been mostly replaced by the tonne, and in the United States by the short ton. One long ton is equal to 2,240 pounds (1,016 kg) or 35 cubic feet (0.9911 m) of salt water with a density of 64 lb/ft (1.025 g/ml). It has some limited use in the United States, most commonly in measuring the displacement of ships, and was the unit prescribed for warships by the Washington Naval Treaty for example battleships were limited to a mass of 35,000 long tons (36,000 t; 39,000 ST).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Short Ton
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A unit of weight equal to 2,000 pounds (907.18474 kg). In the United States it is often called simply ton without distinguishing it from the metric ton (tonne, 1,000 kilograms) or the long ton (2,240 pounds / 1,016.0469088 kilograms); rather, the other two are specifically noted. There are, however, some US applications for which unspecified tons normally means long tons (for example, Navy ships) or metric tons (world grain production figures). Both the long and short ton are defined as 20 hundredweights, but a hundredweight is 100 pounds (45.359237 kg) in the US system (short or net hundredweight) and 112 pounds (50.80234544 kg) in the Imperial system (long or gross hundredweight).

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Gross Ton
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Gross tonnage (GT) is a function of the volume of all ship's enclosed spaces (from keel to funnel) measured to the outside of the hull framing. There is a sliding scale factor. So GT is a kind of capacity-derived index that is used to rank a ship for purposes of determining manning, safety and other statutory requirements and is expressed simply as GT, which is a unitless entity, even though its derivation is tied to the cubic meter unit of volumetric capacity.Tonnage measurements are now governed by an IMO Convention (International Convention on Tonnage Measurement of Ships, 1969 (London-Rules)), which applies to all ships built after July 1982. In accordance with the Convention, the correct term to use now is GT, which is a function of the moulded volume of all enclosed spaces of the ship.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Net Ton
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Net tonnage (NT) is based on a calculation of the volume of all cargo spaces of the ship. It indicates a vessels earning space and is a function of the moulded volume of all cargo spaces of the ship.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Heading Down Bearing
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: The horizontal direction heading down a Q-Route (e.g. D to C to B to A), expressed as the angular distance from true north. It is usually measured from 0 at the reference direction clockwise through 360.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Expression intended to indicate an area of a reef or other projection from the bottom of a body of water which periodically extends above and is submerged below the surface. Also referred to as dries or uncovers.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Awash

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Cetacean
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Any of an order (Cetacea) of aquatic mostly marine mammals that includes the whales, dolphins, porpoises, and related forms and that have a torpedo-shaped nearly hairless body, paddle-shaped forelimbs but no hind limbs, one or two nares opening externally at the top of the head, and a horizontally flattened tail used for locomotion.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Pinniped
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Any of an order or suborder (Pinnipedia) of aquatic carnivorous mammals (such as a seal or walrus) with all four limbs modified into flippers.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Fish
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Vertebrate cold blooded animal with gills, living in water.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Turtle
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Any of an order (Testudines synonym Chelonia) of terrestrial, freshwater, and marine reptiles that have a toothless horny beak and a shell of bony dermal plates usually covered with horny shields enclosing the trunk and into which the head, limbs, and tail usually may be withdrawn.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Bird
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Any of a class (Aves) of warm-blooded vertebrates distinguished by having the body more or less completely covered with feathers and the forelimbs modified as wings.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Sirenian
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Any of an order (Sirenia) of aquatic herbivorous mammals (such as a manatee, dugong, or Steller's sea cow) that have large forelimbs resembling paddles, no hind limbs, and a flattened tail resembling a fin.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Otter (animal)
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: 507:Otter (animal) (missing definition)

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Polar bear
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A large creamy-white carnivorous bear (Ursus maritimus synonym Thalarctos maritimus) that inhabits arctic regions.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Sea snake
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Any of numerous venomous aquatic chiefly viviparous elapid snakes of warm seas.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Coral Reef
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A reef, often of large extent, composed chiefly of coral and its derivatives.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Category of Fishing Facility
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: Classification of fishing facility provided based on different fishing methods.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Fishing Stake
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: Poles or stakes placed in shallow water to outline a fishing ground or to catch fish.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Fish Trap
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A structure (usually portable) for catching fish.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Fish Weir
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A fence of stakes or stones set in a river or along the shore to trap fish.

S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:label: Tunny Net
S100FC:listedValue.S100FC:definition: A net built at sea for catching tunny.

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Buried Depth

S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:name: Maximum Flight Level
S100FC:S100_FC_SimpleAttribute.S100FC:definition: A maximum surface of constant atmospheric pressure which is related to a specific pressure datum, (1,013.2 hectopascal (hPa) or 29.92 inches) and is separated from the consecutive flight levels by a pressure interval corresponding to 500 feet (152.4 m.)

S100FC:uom.S100Base:definition: a unit of length equal to 12 inches, 1/6 of a fathom, or 30.480 centimetres

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The predefined span on clearance, determined after assessing geographical and Mine Countermeasure (MCM) conditions, within which a designated Q Route operates.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Detection Date Range
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The range in years in which the object was originally reported

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Multiplicity of Features
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The number of features of identical character that exist as a co-located group.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Online Resource
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Information about online sources from which a resource or data can be obtained.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Topmark
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A characteristic shape secured at the top of a buoy or beacon to aid in its identification.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Feature Name
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Provides the name of an entity, defines the national language of the name, and provides the option to display the name at various system display settings.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Fixed Date Range
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: An active period of a single fixed event or occurrence, as the date range between discrete start and end dates.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Altitude Range
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Altitude range encompasses both the maximum and minimum heights (AGL - above ground level) above the surface level, representing the vertical span from the highest to the lowest point of the feature.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Altitude
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: (1) The vertical distance of a level, a point or an object considered as a point (but not affixed to the surface of the earth), measured from a given datum, usually mean sea level. See also elevation and height. (2) In astronomy, the vertical angle between the plane of the horizon and the line to a celestial body. See also angle of depression and angle of elevation.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical Clearance Safe

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Last Source Information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The source and the sensor used of the subsequent report of the object.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Textual information about the feature. The information may be provided as a string of text or as a file name of a single external text file that contains the text.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: First Source Information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The source and the sensor used of the original report of the object.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Horizontal Clearance Fixed
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The horizontal clearance measured between two points for a fixed span.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical Uncertainty
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The best estimate of the vertical accuracy of depths, heights, vertical distances and vertical clearances.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Frequency Pair
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A pair of frequencies for transmitting and receiving radio signals. The shore station transmits and receives on the frequencies indicated.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vessel Measurements Specification
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Combinations of values of measurable characteristics or dimensions of vessels, used to specify size and tonnage ranges.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Surface Characteristics
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The general nature of the material of which the land surface or the seabed is composed.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Magnetic Information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Indication of the collective magnetic attributes and characteristics associated with an object, as measured and quantified through various magnetic detection methods.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Speed
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Rate of motion. The terms speed and velocity are often used interchangeably, but speed is a scalar, having magnitude only, while velocity is a vector quantity, having both magnitude and direction.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vertical Clearance Fixed
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The vertical clearance measured from the horizontal plane towards a fixed (non-opening) feature overhead.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Source Identification
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A complex attribute that provides detailed information about the origin of a source, including the agency responsible for its production, the nation of origin, the type of source, and a unique identifier for the source.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Horizontal Position Uncertainty
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The best estimate of the accuracy of a position.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector Characteristics
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Describes the characteristics of a light sector.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Orientation
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: (1) The angular distance measured from true north to the major axis of the feature. (2) In ECDIS, the mode in which information on the ECDIS is being presented. Typical modes include: north-up - as shown on a nautical chart, north is at the top of the display; Ships head-up - based on the actual heading of the ship, (e.g. Ships gyrocompass); course-up display - based on the course or route being taken.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Direction Heading
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Indicates the the angular orientation from true north, often measured in degrees clockwise, along a specified route.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Flight Level
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The range of altitudes within which an object or aircraft operates, encompassing the highest and lowest points of constant atmospheric pressure in aviation, each separated from the next by a 500-foot interval, measured in relation to 1,013.2 hectopascals (hPa) or 29.92 inches of mercury.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Vessel Speed Limit
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The maximum allowed rate of travel for a vessel in an area in knots.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Periodic Date Range
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The active period of a recurring event or occurrence.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Shape Information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Textual information about the shape of a non-standard topmark.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Light Sector
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Signal Sequence
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: The sequence of times occupied by intervals of light/sound and eclipse/silence for all “light characteristics” or sound signals.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector Information
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: Additional textual information about a light sector.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Directional Character
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A directional light is a light illuminating a sector of very narrow angle and intended to mark a direction to follow.

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector Limit
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. The sector limit specifies the limits of the sector In a clockwise direction around the central feature (for example a light).

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector Limit Two
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. Sector limit two specifies the second limit of the sector. The order of sector limit one and sector limit two is clockwise around the central feature (for example a light).

S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:name: Sector Limit One
S100FC:S100_FC_ComplexAttribute.S100FC:definition: A sector is the part of a circle between two straight lines drawn from the centre to the circumference. Sector limit one specifies the first limit of the sector. The order of sector limit one and sector limit two is clockwise around the central feature (for example a light).

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Installation Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An installation buoy is a buoy used for loading tankers with gas or oil.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Depth Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A water area whose depth is within a defined range of values.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radio Calling-In Point
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A designated position at which vessels are required to report to a traffic control centre. Also called reporting point or radio reporting point.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Patrol Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A defined area on land or over water which is patrolled by a controlling or regulatory authority.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Checkpoint
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An official location at which to register, declare and/or inspect goods and/or people.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Marine Management Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area which is managed and/or monitored by a controlling authority to protect the marine environment and ensure restrictions applicable to that area, or marine activities carried out within the area conform to current legislation/regulations.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Depth Contour
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A line connecting points of equal water depth which is sometimes significantly displaced outside of soundings, symbols, and other chart detail for clarity as well as generalization. Depth contours therefore often represent an approximate location of the line of equal depth as related to the surveyed line delineated on the source.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Environmentally Sensitive Sea Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A generic term which may be used to describe a wide range of areas, considered sensitive for a variety of environmental reasons.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Road
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A route with a specially prepared surface that is intended for use by wheeled vehicles or pedestrians.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: River
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A relatively large natural stream of water.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Military Practice Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within which naval, military or aerial exercises are carried out.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Discoloured Water
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Unnatural coloured areas in the sea which may or may not indicate the existence of shoals.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cardinal Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A cardinal buoy is used in conjunction with the compass to indicate where the mariner may find the best navigable water. It is placed in one of the four quadrants (North, East, South and West), bounded by inter-cardinal bearings from the point marked.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Safe Water Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A safe water buoy is used to indicate that there is navigable water around the mark.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radio Station
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A place equipped to transmit radio waves. Such a station may be either stationary or mobile, and may also be provided with a radio receiver.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Military Exercise Airspace
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Airspace of defined dimension identified by area on Earth's surface where activities must be confined because of their nature and/or where limitations may be imposed on aircraft.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Contiguous Zone
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A zone contiguous to a coastal State's Territorial Sea, which may not extend beyond 24 nautical miles from the baselines from which the breadth of the Territorial Sea is measured. The coastal State may exercise certain control in this zone subject to the provisions of International Law.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Normal Baseline
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The low-water line along the coast as marked on large-scale charts officially recognized by the coastal State. In the case of islands situated on atolls or of islands having fringing reefs, the baseline for measuring the breadth of the territorial sea is the seaward low-water line of the reef, as shown by the appropriate symbol on charts officially recognized by the coastal State. Where a low-tide elevation is situated wholly or partly at a distance not exceeding the breadth of the territorial sea from the mainland or an island, the low-water line on that elevation may be used as the baseline for measuring the breadth of the territorial sea.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cable Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area which contains one or more submarine cables.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Continental Shelf Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The Continental Shelf of a coastal State comprises the seabed and subsoil of the submarine areas that extend beyond its Territorial Sea throughout the natural prolongation of its land territory to the outer edge of the continental margin, or to a distance of 200 nautical miles from the baselines from which the breadth of the Territorial Sea is measured where the outer edge of the continental margin does not extend up to that distance.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Internal Waters
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Waters on the landward side of the baseline of the territorial sea.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Administration Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A defined area within which a jurisdiction applies. It may or may not be named.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Bollard
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Small shaped post, mounted on a wharf or dolphin used to secure ship's lines.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dolphin
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A post or group of posts, used for mooring or warping a vessel, or as an aid to navigation. The dolphin may be in the water, on a wharf or on the beach.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radar Range
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Indicates the coverage of a sea area by a radar surveillance station. Inside this area a vessel may request shore-based radar assistance, particularly in poor visibility.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Isolated Danger Beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An isolated danger beacon is a beacon erected on an isolated danger of limited extent, which has navigable water all around it.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Isolated Danger Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An isolated danger buoy is a buoy moored on or above an isolated danger of limited extent, which has navigable water all around it.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Submarine Transit Lane
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A lane where submarines may navigate under water or at the surface.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: MaritimeSafetyInformationArea (missing Name)
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: MaritimeSafetyInformationArea (missing definition)

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Airspace Restriction
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The airspace above a designated land or water area through which flight is prohibited or restricted.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sounding
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Measured or charted depth of water (may be a drying height), or the measurement of such a depth, which has been reduced to a vertical datum.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Traffic Separation Scheme Boundary
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The outer limit of a traffic lane part or a traffic separation scheme roundabout.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dumping Ground
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A sea area where dredged material or other potentially more harmful material, for example explosives, chemical waste, is deliberately deposited.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Airport/Airfield
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A defined area on land (including any buildings, installations and equipment) intended to be used either wholly or in part for the arrival, departure and surface movement of aircraft.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Foul Ground
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Areas over which it is safe to navigate but which should be avoided for anchoring, taking the ground or ground fishing.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light Air Obstruction
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An air obstruction light is a light marking an obstacle which constitutes a danger to air navigation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Mooring Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A buoy secured to the bottom by permanent moorings with means for mooring a vessel by use of its anchor chain or mooring lines.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Underwater/Awash Rock
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A concreted mass of stony material or coral which dries, is awash or is below the water surface.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cable Overhead
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A single continuous rope-like bundle consisting of multiple strands of fiber, plastic, metal, and/or glass, which is supported by structures such as poles or pylons and passing over or nearby navigable waters.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Controlled Airspace
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Designated airspace within which some or all aircraft may be subjected to air traffic control.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Obstruction
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: In marine navigation, anything that hinders or prevents movement, particularly anything that endangers or prevents passage of a vessel. The term is usually used to refer to an isolated danger to navigation, such as a sunken rock or pinnacle.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fishing Ground
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A water area in which fishing is frequently carried on.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fishing Facility
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A structure for fishing purposes which can be an obstruction to ships in general. The position of these structures may vary frequently over time.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Navigation System
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Any visual or electronic device which provides point-to-point guidance information or position data

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Traffic Separation Scheme Crossing
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A defined area where traffic lanes cross.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Traffic Separation Scheme Lane Part
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area within defined limits in which one-way traffic is established. Natural obstacles, including those forming separation zones, may constitute a boundary.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Territorial Sea Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A belt of water of a defined breadth but not exceeding 12 nautical miles measured seaward from the territorial sea baseline.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Lateral Beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A lateral beacon is used to indicate the port or starboard hand side of the route to be followed. They are generally used for well defined channels and are used in conjunction with a conventional direction of buoyage.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Coast Guard Station
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A station at which a visual/radio/radar marine watch is kept either continuously or at certain times only.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Separation Zone or Line
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A zone or line separating the traffic lanes in which ships are proceeding in opposite, or nearly opposite directions; or separating a traffic lane from the adjacent sea area; or separating traffic lanes designated for particular classes of ships proceeding in the same direction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Bottom Feature
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A significant configuration of underwater topography

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Archipelagic Baseline
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Straight baselines joining the outermost points of the outermost islands and drying reefs of the archipelago provided that within such baselines are included the main islands and an area in which the ratio of the area of the water to the area of the land, including atolls, is between 1 to 1 and 9 to 1.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Small Bottom Object
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Underwater feature appearing mine-like on a sonar image (AML)

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Exclusive Economic Zone
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area, not exceeding 200 nautical miles from the baselines from which the breadth of the territorial sea is measured, subject to a specific legal regime established in the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea under which the coastal state has certain rights and jurisdiction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Radar Station
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A station with a transmitter emitting pulses of ultra-high frequency radio waves which are reflected by solid objects and are detected upon their return to the sending station.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Diving Location
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Location where civilian diving activities take place.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Restricted Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A specified area designated by an appropriate authority within which navigation is restricted in accordance with certain specified conditions.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cable Submarine
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An assembly of wires or fibres, or a wire rope or chain, which has been laid underwater or buried beneath the seafloor.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Wreck
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The ruined remains of a stranded or sunken vessel which has been rendered useless.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Q-Route
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A pre-planned dormant channel and/or route, surveyed for mine-like contacts during peacetime that can be 'activated' to provide shipping with safe navigable routes.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: CompletenessOfProductSpecification (missing Name)
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: CompletenessOfProductSpecification (missing definition)

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Rescue Station
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A place where equipment for saving life at sea is maintained.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Cardinal Beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A cardinal beacon is used in conjunction with the compass to indicate where the mariner may find the best navigable water. It is placed in one of the four quadrants (North, East, South and West), bounded by inter-cardinal bearings from the point marked.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light Vessel
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A distinctively marked vessel anchored or moored at a charted point, to serve as an aid to navigation. By night, it displays a characteristic light(s) and is usually equipped with other devices, such as fog signal, submarine sound signal, and radio-beacon, to assist navigation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Fishery Zone
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The offshore zone in which exclusive fishing rights and management are held by the coastal nation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Dredged Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area of the bottom of a body of water which has been deepened by dredging.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Ferry Route
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A route in a body of water where a ferry crosses from one shoreline to another.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Shoreline Construction
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A fixed artificial structure in the water and/or adjoining the land. It may also refer to features such as training walls, which are not necessarily connected to, nor form part of the shoreline.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Caution Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Generally, an area where the mariner has to be made aware of circumstances influencing the safety of navigation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Deep Water Route Part
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area of a deep water route within which ships proceed in the same direction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Current - Non-Gravitational
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Any current that is caused by other than tide producing forces.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Data Coverage
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A geographical area that describes the coverage and extent of spatial objects.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Seabed Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A region of the seabed including the material of which it is composed and its physical characteristics. Also called nature of bottom, character (or characteristics) of the bottom, or quality of the bottom.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Special Purpose/General Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A special purpose buoy is primarily used to indicate an area or feature, the nature of which is apparent from reference to a chart, Sailing Directions or Notices to Mariners.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light Sectored
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A light presenting different appearances (in particular, different colours) over various parts of the horizon of interest to maritime navigation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Ice Line
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The Ice Line provides a measured, observed or estimated limit of the ice infested waters. (ECDIS Ice Objects Version 3.0)

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Anchorage Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An area in which vessels or seaplanes anchor or may anchor.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Lateral Buoy
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A lateral buoy is used to indicate the port or starboard hand side of the route to be followed. They are generally used for well-defined channels and are used in conjunction with a conventional direction of buoyage.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Traffic Separation Scheme Roundabout
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A routeing measure comprising a separation point or circular separation zone and a circular traffic lane within defined limits. Traffic within the roundabout is separated by moving in a counter-clockwise direction around the separation point or zone.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Deep Water Route Centreline
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The Deep Water route centreline indicates the centreline of a route, the width of which is not explicitly defined.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light Float
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A boat-like structure used instead of a light buoy in waters where strong streams or currents are experienced, or when a greater elevation than that of a light buoy is necessary.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Light All Around
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: An all around light is a light that is visible over the whole horizon of interest to marine navigation and having no change in the characteristics of the light.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Coastline
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: The line where shore and water meet. Shoreline and coastline are generally used synonymously.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Sea Area/Named Water Area
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A geographically defined part of the sea or other navigable waters. It may be specified within its limits by its proper name.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Drop Zone
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Area designated for landing personnel and/or equipment by parachute

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Conveyor
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A mechanical device for conveying bulk material or people using an endless moving belt or series of rollers.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Line of Delimitation
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A line drawn on a map or chart depicting the separation of any type of maritime jurisdiction.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Straight Territorial Sea Baseline
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: Straight baselines are a system of straight lines joining specified or discrete points on the low-water line, usually known as straight baseline turning points. Straight baselines are used in delimitation.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Safe Water Beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A safe water beacon is used to indicate that there is navigable water around the mark.

S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:name: Special Purpose/General Beacon
S100FC:S100_FC_FeatureType.S100FC:definition: A special purpose beacon is primarily used to indicate an area or feature, the nature of which is apparent from reference to a chart, Sailing Directions or Notices to Mariners.
